The Auditor-General has painted a bleak picture of municipalities' finances. eNCA political editor Vuyo Mvoko is following the story. #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Municipalities have lost a shocking R32-billion for the 2018-19 financial year to corruption and irregular expenditure. That's an increase of around R7-billion from the previous year. WATCH: Auditor General releases local govt audit results In the report, Auditor-General Kimi Makwetu outlines how funds were allocated to municipalities and how they were spent. He says administrative and governance lapses lead to weak accountability. Findings revealed there is an overall decline in the quality of municipal financial records, and the audit report also shows an increase in irregular, unauthorised and wasteful expenditure. READ: Pay for municipal services, Salga urges Makwetu also slammed municipalities for not adhering to his office's recommendations. The Auditor-General's office now has the power to hold individuals responsible for the missing billions. Auditor-General Kimi Makwetu will release local government audit results for the 2018-19 financial year.